04541nam a22005415i 9780773559776DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735597767 a10.1515/97807735597762doi  a(DE-B1597)656865  a(OCoLC)1108756085  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE361.N6bC34 2019 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a340.0607162231 aCahill, Barry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProfessional Autonomy and the Public Interest :bThe Barristers' Society and Nova Scotia's Lawyers, 1825–2005 /cBarry Cahill. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- t“Wholesome Control” -- tPart One -- tFrom Statutory Regulation to Law Society -- tThe Society and the Bar: Road to Annexation -- tThe Society under the Barristers and Solicitors Act -- tBrave New World -- tBack to the Future -- tPart Two -- t“Nova Scotia's Watergate”: The Society and the Marshall Inquiry Report -- tMade in Manitoba: The Society and the Legal Profession Act -- tThe Society and Professional Regulation -- tThe Society and Administration -- tThe Society and Legal Education -- tThe Society and Continuing Professional Development -- tConclusion: Self-Regulation and the Public Interest -- tChronology -- tOfficers and Senior Officials -- tThe Barristers' Library -- tBibliographical Note -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFormed in 1825, the Nova Scotia Barristers' Society is the second-oldest law society in common-law Canada, after the Law Society of Ontario. Yet despite its founders' ambitions, it did not become the regulator of the legal profession in Nova Scotia for nearly seventy-five years. In this institutional history of the Nova Scotia Barristers' Society from its inception to the Legal Profession Act of 2005, Barry Cahill provides a chronological exploration of the profession's regulation in Nova Scotia and the critical role of the society. Based on extensive research conducted on internal documents, legislative records, and legal and general-interest periodicals and newspapers, Professional Autonomy and the Public Interest demonstrates that the inauguration of the Nova Scotia Barristers' Society was the first giant step on the long road to self-regulation. Highlighting the inherent tensions between protection of professional self-interest and protection of the larger public interest, Cahill explains that while this radical innovation was opposed by both lawyers and judges, it was ultimately imposed by the Liberal government in 1899. In light of emerging models of regulation in the twenty-first century, Professional Autonomy and the Public Interest is a timely look back at the origins of professional regulatory bodies and the evolution of law affecting the legal profession in Atlantic Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLawzNova ScotiaxSocieties, etcxHistory. 0aLawzNova ScotiaxSocieties, etc.xHistory. 0aLawyerszNova ScotiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773559776?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773559776423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773559776/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyt